The anatomy of workflows for analyzing isobarically labeled mass spectrometry data in proteomics

Piotr Prostko, Joris Van Houtven

January 13, 2021

1 General intro

The text below is just a quick and dirty sketch of the future content

In this notebook series, we explore how different data analysis strategies affect the outcome of a proteomics experiment based on isobaric labeling and mass spectrometry. Each analysis strategy or workflow can be divided up into different components. In this notebook specifically, we give an overview of the different workflow components and briefly describe the data set used.

Analyzing this kind of data is not a simple matter, because there is quite some complexity and experimental variability involved due to the pooling of samples and combining of data from different intrument runs, respectively. On top of that, the data is also quite hierarchical in nature.

If you need a refresher on any of those, expand this section. _stuff about proteins, sample pooling, and the large amount of variability between MS runs (as opposed to, e.g.NGS data. You can copy that info from this paper: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1TE_2e_tWsIU5fNtPpIwN7CjJsetgPqP5/view?usp=sharing)_

2 Workflow components

The table below shows an overview of the many components that make up a workflow for performing a differential expression analysis (DEA). This list is probably not exhaustive, but for each of those components a decision has to be made. Note that we have made a dichotomy between data-driven and model-based approaches.

Data-driven approach Model-based approach
Component Default Variant 1 Variant 2 Component Default Variant 1 Variant 2
unit scale intensity+log2 intensity ratio+log2 unit scale intensity+log2 intensity ratio+log2 VSN?
imputation none imputation none
imputation-level none imputation-level none
thresholding remove NA and isolationInterference thresholding remove NA and isolationInterference
outliers none outliers none
normalisation-level PSM sumerization level none PSM to peptide PSM to peptide
normalisation CONSTANd NOMAD median sweeping summarization none median sum
sumerization level PSM to peptide to protein normalisation-level PSM peptide peptide
summarization median iPQF sum normalisation LMM formulation from Piotrs thesis Vary main effects, interactions, fixed or random effects, variance structure
visualization level protein visualization level protein
DEA moderated ttest wilcoxon some permutation test DEA LMM (peptide:run + LIMMA) DEqMS (no within-protein correlation correction) LMM (protein:run + LIMMA)
multiple testing corr. BH multiple testing corr. BH
reference sample no reference sample no
modeling framework frequentist modeling framework frequentist

Each of the notebooks in this series takes the default approach, except for one component for which different variants are explored in detail. We chose the unit scale, normalization method, summarization method and DEA method as most interesting components to investigate, because on one hand we expect them to be impactful and on the other hand they are the ones we see varied and published about the most. We have made a non-systematic, non-exhaustive, publicly available list of publications and software packages related to analyzing proteomics data. You are very welcome to suggest edits and additions to this public repository.

3 Data set

The data used in this notebook series is a subset of the SpikeIn-5mix-MS2 (Five controlled mixtures with technical replicates) data set used in the initial publication on MSstatsTMT. As shown in the figure below, we use only subsetting to mixtures 1,2 and techreps 1,2

Below the first few records of the data (in wide format) are printed out to see what we will be dealing with.

# Venn diagram of proteins identified  across MS runs
unique.prot=dat.w %>%

  distinct(Protein) %>%
